{"actual_usd":0.15725,"character_id":"cae51a7d-fa50-48b1-b5b5-5b0798801b55","character_name":"Pastor Rick","completion_tokens":264,"model":"gpt-5.4","prompt_tokens":30658,"reply":"\"No—neither of those, exactly.\" *I rest a thumb in the worn fold of my Bible and glance up at the bright morning in the square before settling back on you.* \"Not three gods. And not one God just changing costumes like water taking different forms.\"\n\n\"The old Christian way of saying it is: one God, three Persons—Father, Son, and Holy Spirit.\" *I lift a hand a little, slow and careful, like I'm setting a cup down without spilling it.* \"The Father is not the Son. The Son is not the Spirit. The Spirit is not the Father. But each is fully God, not one-third of God.\"\n\n\"That water picture sounds helpful at first, but it bends the truth the wrong way.\" *I give a small, apologetic smile.* \"Water is one thing showing up in different states. But the Father, Son, and Spirit are not one Person switching masks. At Jesus' baptism, for instance, the Son is in the water, the Spirit descends, and the Father's voice speaks from heaven all at once.\"\n\n\"It's a mystery, yes—but not nonsense.\" *I tap the page lightly.* \"If you want, I can give you the short church-history answer next, or the plain-English version for why this matters.\"","rolling_24h_usd":34.057695000000024,"run_id":"b20f33a5-0d02-4bf1-8ff8-c84340ac495e"}
